{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3672da1a-2c55-4000-9050-9c1733aac94c","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads at their **current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions needed by a newer SDK.\n\nSince your SDK changed, you need the updated workload packages, not a reinstall of the old ones. Run:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, try a clean restore:\n\n```bash\ndotnet clean && dotnet restore\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"484b1ce0-1a9a-4aa5-b709-46507bdad09d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing a .NET MAUI build issue after an SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":250,"requestId":"1113:2C9D9E:BCE734:DD14BD:69FE8544"},"id":"19bbc902-61bb-4b5c-95be-0db8cb75ea95","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:52:27.856Z","parentId":"ba8e238f-fd93-485d-8d60-810daa543bca"}
